# Public Prosecutor _v_ Tang Yan Jiang Jeffrey  

### \[2022\] SGMC 23

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">Magistrate's Court Notice No. 902076 of 2019, Magistrate's Appeals Nos. 9059-2022-01 and 9059-2022-02</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">04 May 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">Magistrates Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Chua Wei Yuan</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">DPP Joseph Gwee (Attorney-General's Chambers) for the Prosecution; Raymond Lye and Ashley Phua (Union Law LLP) for the Accused.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Public Prosecutor — Tang Yan Jiang Jeffrey</td></tr></tbody></table>

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9059/2022/01-02.\]

4 May 2022

### District Judge Chua Wei Yuan:

## Brief facts

1       The accused, Tang Yan Jiang Jeffrey (“Mr Tang”), pleaded guilty to a single charge of unlawfully stalking his ex-girlfriend (“V”) under s 7(1) of the Protection from Harassment Act (Cap 256A, 2015 Rev Ed) (“PHA”), as follows:

> You … are charged that you between 3 March 2019 to 25 October 2019, at various locations in Singapore, did unlawfully stalk one \[V\], by engaging in a course of conduct which involved acts associated with stalking, _to wit_:

>> a.    On 3 March 2019, by ringing \[V’s\] doorbell continuously;

>> b.    On 19 May 2019, by using your vehicle … to block \[V’s\] vehicle and sending her an e-mail on that day;

>> c.    On 20 May 2019, by calling \[V’s\] friend to look for \[V\];

>> d.    On 7 June 2019, at around 12.20am, by hanging a packet of medication at \[V’s\] door and e-mailing her that you would not take the medication back, such that if you died, she would be the cause of it;

>> e.    On 9 and 11 June 2019, by e-mailing \[V\] that you had visited her house and other places frequented by her, to look for her;

>> f.    By e-mailing \[V\] a screenshot of a message you sent to her colleagues in a \[WhatsApp\][\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) group “UAG 2019”, stating, “She’s a fucker. Don’t trust this bitch. Name \[V’s name\]”;

>> g.    By e-mailing \[V\] a screenshot of a message you sent to her colleagues in a \[WhatsApp\] group “PN Broadcast”, stating, “This lady is ready for a fuck but she will cheat your money. Be careful. Yes. She shallow sperm. Haaaaaa”;

>> h.    On 30 August 2019, at around 9.53pm, by commenting on a picture of \[V\] on Facebook,[^2]_namely_, the Facebook page of Singapore Recreation Club, “Be careful of this lady \[V’s name\]. Act holy, go church, act hypocrite, she’s a bastard. She can ruin your family.”

>> i.    On 1 October 2019, by going to \[V’s\] residence and knocking and kicking on her door, whilst using threatening language and alleging that \[V\] owed you money, and also by trailing \[V\] from her condominium carpark to Bukit Batok Police Station;

>> j.    By sending \[V\] multiple other distressing e-mails and text messages from 19 May to 25 October 2019;

> Thereby causing harassment and alarm to \[V\], when you ought to have known that your conduct was likely to cause harassment and alarm to \[V\], and you have thereby committed an offence under \[s 7(1) PHA\] and punishable under \[s 7(6) PHA\]\[.\]

2       Briefly, Mr Tang—then about 50 years old—and V—then about 52 years old—had been in a romantic relationship for several years. The pair broke up in February 2019. Shortly after, Mr Tang started to stalk V, with a view to salvaging their relationship.

3       In summary, 64 discrete incidents were disclosed in both the statement of facts (“SOF”) and in the charge, over a period of 33 discrete calendar days spread over what appears to be nearly 8 months (_ie_, 3 March 2019–25 October 2019). These incidents are enumerated at **Annex A**. I should clarify that:

> (a)     In arriving at this incident count, each e-mail was counted as a discrete incident, and the chain of text messages was counted as a single incident.

> (b)     The exact date on which Mr Tang sent the WhatsApp messages to the “UAG 2019” and “PN Broadcast” groups is unclear, but I have assumed that they both took place on 5 March 2019, being the date that he apologised for sending the messages to the “UAG 2019” group. There is no indication that it took place before 3 March 2019 and, at any rate, the conduct would not have happened before February 2019 (_ie_, when V broke up with Mr Tang).

4       Of the 64 incidents, 55 involved text messages or e-mails being sent to V. Broadly, these messages could be divided into 3 categories (details of which are in the rightmost column in Annex A):

> (a)     those which contained insults/abuses (_eg_, “slut”, “bloody bastard”, “family of hypocrites”, “fake Christians”, “all Christians fuck together”, “I hope u n your mother die a miserable death”, “I hope u rot in hell”), threats (_eg_, “I will make u famous in SRC”, “I will come for u”), or taunts (_eg_, “go ahead n sue me”, “now u r very famous in SRC”)—of which there were 22 (including borderline cases);

> (b)     those which blamed V (_eg_, “U destroyed my life”) or guilt-tripped V (_eg_, “Left my medicine at your place. I won’t be taking them. I want to leave this world.”) for Mr Tang’s state of being—of which there were 15; and

> (c)     those which either were innocuous or expressed Mr Tang’s love/longing for V or regret—of which there were 18.

5       The remaining 9 incidents were as follows:

> (a)     on 3 March 2019, ringing V’s doorbell;

> (b)     not after 5 March 2019,[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) sending a message to the “UAG 2019” group;

> (c)     on an unknown date,[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4) sending a message to the “PN Broadcast” group;

> (d)     on 19 May 2019 at about 1.00pm, appearing in front of V, and then blocking V’s vehicle with his vehicle;

> (e)     on 20 May 2019 before 4.08pm, calling V’s friend (apparently Mr Tang asked that V call him back, and did not leave his name but said that V would know who he was);[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5)

> (f)     on 7 June 2019 at about 12.20am, hanging a packet of medication on V’s door;

> (g)     on 30 August 2019 at about 9.53pm,[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6) commenting on a picture of V on the Singapore Recreation Club (“SRC”) Facebook page;

> (h)     on 1 October 2019 at about 12.30pm, approaching V at her condominium car park and trailing her to Bukit Batok police station; and

> (i)     on 1 October 2019 at about 9.00pm, kicking V’s door and using threatening language on a security officer.

6       To be sure, I did not take cognisance of two e-mails sent by Mr Tang to V on 7 May 2019[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7) and 24 July 2019,[^8] as well as text-messages sent by Mr Tang to V on 13 March and 15 May 2019,[^9] and on another unknown date.[^10] Although these were exhibited in an Annex submitted by the Prosecution, they were mentioned neither in the charge nor in the SOF. I also note that although the SOF mentions the fact that Mr Tang parked at V’s condominium on occasion(s) unknown,[^11] this was not mentioned in the charge.

## Parties’ positions

7       Mr Tang sought a Mandatory Treatment Order (“MTO”) and, in the alternative, either probation or a fine of $4,000–$5,000.

8       The Prosecution submitted that an MTO was inappropriate, and that Mr Tang should be sentenced to 6–8 months’ imprisonment.

## Decision

9       I sentenced Mr Tang to 9 weeks’ imprisonment. My reasons follow.

### Whether it is appropriate to grant probation

10     Briefly, I find probation inappropriate as Mr Tang is not (and cannot be reasonably likened to) a young “amateur” offender who “\[didn’t\] know any better” (_Lim Li Ling v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] 1 SLR(R) 165</span> (HC) at \[87\]).

### Whether it is appropriate to make an MTO in lieu of a fine/imprisonment

#### Applicable principles

11     Under s 339 of the Criminal Procedure Code (Cap 68, 2012 Rev Ed) (“CPC”), where an offender is convicted of an offence, if the court is satisfied that having regard to the circumstances, including the nature of the offence and the character of the offender, it is expedient to do so, the court may make a MTO requiring the offender to undergo psychiatric treatment for a period not exceeding 36 months.

12     Defence counsel cited _Public Prosecutor v Wen Wee Kin_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] SGDC 380</span> at \[13\], \[26\], \[27\] and \[52\] for the propositions that:

> (a)     a tough punitive response is not always required and perhaps even not preferred when a treatable psychiatric condition had a material bearing on the commission of the offence;

> (b)     the offence need not have flowed entirely or even principally from a psychiatric condition;

> (c)     some reason and intentionality could co-exist with a psychiatric illness as a contributing factor; and

> (d)     it could be expedient to make an MTO even if the psychiatric condition was merely one of the contributing factors to the offence.

13     However, this decision predates the authorities that represent the prevailing law on sentencing of mentally disordered offenders.

14     The applicable principles in sentencing a mentally-disordered offender were considered in _Lim Ghim Peow v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 4 SLR 1287</span> (CA) (“_Lim Ghim Peow_”) at \[25\] and \[36\] _per_ Chao Hick Tin JA (delivering the grounds of decision of the court); _Public Prosecutor v Chong Hou En_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 3 SLR 222</span> (HC) at \[24\]–\[25\], _per_ Chan Seng Onn J and _Public Prosecutor v Low Ji Qing_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] 5 SLR 769</span> (HC) (“_Low Ji Qing_”) at \[44\] _per_ Sundaresh Menon CJ, and are summarised as follows:

> (a)     The existence of a mental disorder is always relevant (or, at least, “generally” relevant (_Low Ji Qing_ at \[44(a)\])) in sentencing, but the manner and extent of its relevance depends on the circumstances of each case (in particular, the nature and severity of such disorder).

> (b)     General deterrence may still be accorded full weight in some circumstances (_eg_, where the mental disorder is not serious or is not causally related to the commission of the offence, and the offence is a serious one), and specific deterrence may remain relevant where the offence is premeditated or where there is a conscious choice to commit the offence.

> (c)     Rehabilitation may take precedence if there is a serious psychiatric condition or mental disorder which renders deterrence less effective (_eg_, where the offender has a significantly impaired ability to appreciate the nature and quality of his actions).

> (d)     Rehabilitation does not necessarily dictate a light sentence; an offender can also be rehabilitated in prison.

> (e)     Retribution and protection should prevail over rehabilitation in cases involving particularly heinous or serious offences, even if the offender is labouring under a serious mental disorder.

> (f)     Having a mental disorder is in most cases a mitigating factor which the court may consider when sentencing the offender. Its significance in terms of mitigating value depends on the factors and principles above. These include specifically factors such as the causal link, the nature and severity of the mental disorder and the offender’s ability to make conscious choices and to appreciate the nature and quality of his actions.

15     In my view, a key inquiry is the nature of the mental disorder and its effect on the offender’s capacity for reason and control. If a mentally disordered offender chooses not to exercise self-control despite being able to, and if punishment can instil fear and deter, then the mental disorder attracts little mitigating weight. Even so, it is important to consider if the offender’s episode is more a maladaptive response to thoughts that are founded on fact and rational, or more an incoherent episode suggesting beliefs that are unreal and irrational.

16     It was explained in _Chong Hou En_ at \[27\]–\[29\]:

> 27    Therefore, in this particular genus of mental disorders, the concept of a causal link may not be particularly useful, or even that relevant for determining the mitigating value to be ascribed to the mental disorder. In my view, where the “severity” of the mental disorder in an individual is assessed with respect to the “frequency” of the criminal act and there is a positive correlation between the “severity” and the “frequency”, then the severity and nature of the individual’s mental disorder ought not to be regarded as a mitigating factor without first examining in detail the _nature_ of the mental disorder, in terms of how it has affected the individual’s ability or capacity to control or refrain himself from committing the criminal acts and whether punishment will be able to instil fear in him and deter him from committing the same criminal acts in future.

> 28     **If** the nature of the mental disorder is such that **the individual retains substantially the mental ability or capacity to control or refrain himself when he commits the criminal acts but he instead chooses not to exercise his self-control, and if** it is also shown that **punishment will be effective in instilling fear in him and thereby deter** him from committing the same criminal acts in the future, I will attribute **very little or no mitigating value** to the presence of the mental disorder.

> 29    If there is evidence to show that the individual is not able or is substantially not able to control or refrain himself from committing the criminal acts because of the mental disorder and similarly, punishment is unlikely to be effective in instilling fear in him and to deter him from committing the same criminal acts in future because of the mental disorder, then the principle of deterrence may be given less weight and rehabilitation may well take precedence provided that the treatment mandated as part of his rehabilitation is going to be effective in treating the mental disorder and in reducing the risk of recidivism. Nevertheless, if the criminal offences committed are just too serious in nature, the principle of rehabilitation may well have to give way to the principle of retribution and protection of the public at large. Ultimately, the factual circumstances will govern how all these different factors, pulling in different directions, are going to interact. The court must judiciously weigh these various factors and arrive at a fair and just sentence that is appropriate in all the circumstances of the case.

17     In _Public Prosecutor v Kong Peng Yee_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 2 SLR 295</span> (CA) (“_Kong Peng Yee_”), Tay Yong Kwang JA (delivering the judgment of the court) explained:

> 65    The psychosis which plagued the Respondent also served to distinguish this case from many of the precedents cited to us. The moral culpability of mentally disordered offenders lies on a spectrum. On the one hand there are offenders who have temporary and situational mental disorders who retain their understanding of their actions and can reason and weigh the consequences. Such offenders often evince the ability to think logically and coherently, borne out by a sophisticated degree of planning and premeditation. The important distinction between such cases and the Respondent’s situation is this. Invariably, the factual basis for such offenders’ actions is a true and rational one, unlike the Respondent’s case. For instance, it could be severe depression caused by intense jealousy and anger over an unfaithful spouse who is in fact in an extra-marital relationship with another person. It could also be depression due to worry and fear that the offender’s employer has found out about the offender’s wrongdoing and is about to terminate the employment or to take disciplinary action against him. In such cases, the underlying reason for the offender’s subsequent criminal conduct is founded on fact, not fantasy or fiction. Hence, in such cases, the mental disorder invariably dissipates or disappears altogether once the underlying situation is removed (for instance by killing the unfaithful spouse or the third party or by killing the employer) and there is no need for psychotic medication or follow-up medical attention. **The mental disorder in such cases can only ameliorate to a limited extent the criminal conduct because the offender’s mind is still rational. In such cases, deterrence and retribution should still feature because depression, even if severe, cannot be a licence to kill or to harm others.**

> 66     **On the other hand**, there are offenders whose mental disorders impair severely their ability to understand the nature and consequences of their acts, to make reasoned decisions or to control their impulses. The Respondent’s brief psychotic episode was in this category. He exhibited **incoherent and irrational behaviour before, during and after the offence**. He muttered incoherently to people he did not know. He stabbed and slashed unrelentingly at an elderly, defenceless woman with two dangerous weapons. Whatever seemingly rational decisions that he made were premised on totally unreal facts and completely irrational thoughts. His **actions were not merely a maladaptive response to a difficult or depressive true situation, such as a temporary loss of self-control. Instead, they emanated from an impaired mind.**

18     The effect of the mental disorder on the offender’s capacity for reason and control was, in _Chong Yee Ka v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 4 SLR 309</span> (HC) (“_Chong Yee Ka_”) at \[64\], framed in terms of the directness of the causal nexus. There, See Kee Oon J concluded that the appellant’s major depressive disorder and mild obsessive-compulsive disorder were not causally linked to her offending (_ie_, voluntarily causing hurt to a foreign domestic worker). Instead, it was “far more plausible and reasonable” to conclude that the psychiatric conditions would have caused her to have difficulties controlling her emotions and impulses and would have contributed to her loss of self-control that led to the commission of the offences, but that they did not directly cause her to commit violent acts.

#### The psychiatric reports

19     In this case, 4 psychiatric reports/memoranda were written in total. Broadly, Mr Tang denied wanting to harm V, and claimed that he had drunk heavily prior to the offence and was unable to recall the events fully afterward (_eg_, he recalled or realised what he had done only when he saw the e-mails that he had sent to V).

20      **First**, Dr Charles Mak issued a memorandum on 28 February 2020, stating that Mr Tang had major depressive disorder (“Major DD”) and Alcohol dependence, and that he was receiving counselling for his alcohol use and required psychiatric medication and follow-up.

21      **Second**, Dr Lim Yun Chin (Mr Tang’s psychiatrist from Raffles Hospital) issued a report based on 2 visits dated 29 October and 5 November 2020.

> (a)     He noted that Mr Tang, based on the Beck Depression Inventory, was undergoing moderate depression (“Moderate DD”) with a score of 20.

> (b)     He opined that the major depression and alcohol abuse played a contributory link to the commission of the alleged offence in the sense that:

>> (i)       the excess use of alcohol would invariably lead to loss of self-control, disinhibition and rash behaviour (which includes harassment); and

>> (ii)       the depressive symptoms caused immense emotional pain and in his impaired mind at the time, the only way to “cure” his depression was for V to return to him.

> (c)     He opined that it is unlikely that Mr Tang’s behaviour will recur, as his attempt to salvage the relationship has subsided.

> (d)     He recommended that Mr Tang continue treatment at IMH for depression and alcohol dependence.

22      **Third**, Dr Lambert Low (from the Institute of Mental Health (“IMH”)) issued a report based on a visit dated 22 April 2021.

> (a)     He opined that Mr Tang was suffering from Major DD and alcohol dependence at the material time of the offences, and that his judgment was likely clouded by his low mood and drinking habits.

> (b)     He opined that Mr Tang would benefit from continued treatment and counselling with the National Addictions Management Service.

23      **Finally**, Dr Mohamed Zakir Karuvetil (from IMH)—the appointed psychiatrist for the purpose of s 339 CPC—issued a report based on an examination on 26 November 2021.

> (a)     He opined that Mr Tang suffered from Moderate DD, which is in full remission, and Alcohol Use Disorder (“AUD”) which is now in partial remission, and that his Moderate DD & AUD, especially alcoholic intoxication, had contributed to the index offences.

> (b)     He opined that Mr Tang would benefit from relapse prevention counselling for his AUD, that his next review at IMH was scheduled in 2 months’ time, and that he had not been prescribed any psychotropic medications.

> (c)     He opined that Mr Tang was suitable for a 12-month MTO.

24     At this juncture, I note that the psychiatrists appeared divided on whether Mr Tang had Moderate DD or Major DD. Dr Mak and Dr Low opined that Mr Tang had Major DD while Dr Lim and Dr Zakir opined that he had Moderate DD.

25     I find that Mr Tang’s depression was moderate, albeit at the borderline between Moderate DD and Major DD. On the one hand, Dr Zakir was both the appointed psychiatrist and the most recent attending physician, and enjoyed corroborative history from a family member; and Dr Lim reached his conclusion after having administered a diagnostic instrument. The score of 20, as recorded by Dr Lim, would indicate depression at the borderline between “moderately severe” and “severe”. On the other hand, Dr Mak’s had indicated his diagnosis as an unexplained assertion in a brief memorandum. Dr Low—unlike Dr Zakir—did not have the benefit of corroborative history, because Mr Tang declined to bring a family member for this purpose.

#### Whether it is expedient to make an MTO

26     I can accept that the appointed psychiatrist certified that Mr Tang was suffering from Moderate DD and AUD, that these were contributing factors to his offending; and that he was susceptible to treatment and showed propensity for reform.

27     However, I do not think that an MTO is suitable in this case.

28      **First**, I am not satisfied that there is a sufficiently close causal nexus between Mr Tang’s Moderate DD or AUD and his offending.[\[note: 12\]](#Ftn_12) In this regard, none of the psychiatrists said that Mr Tang’s Moderate DD or AUD had a _causal_ link to his offending, in the sense that it impaired his self-control.

> (a)     Dr Zakir said that the DD or AUD (especially intoxication) “had contributed” to the offences.

> (b)     Dr Lim said that they “played a contributory link” to the commission of the alleged offences, in that the excess use of alcohol would invariably disinhibit Mr Tang, while the depressive symptoms caused immense emotional pain and, in his impaired mind at the time, the only way to “cure” it was for V to return to him.

> (c)     Dr Low said that Mr Tang’s “judgment was likely clouded by his low mood and drinking habits”, without commenting on the effect of what he considered to be Mr Tang’s Major DD on his offending.

29     Indeed, I would find that the link between Mr Tang’s psychiatric conditions and his offending is not sufficiently direct.

> (a)     In the case of Mr Tang’s Moderate DD, the depression would cloud his judgment (according to Dr Low) or cause immense emotional pain and impair his mind (according to Dr Lim), such that Mr Tang would see V’s return to him as being the only “cure”. However, even so, Mr Tang would still have to take the further step of trying to procure V’s return to him; the depression does not _necessarily_ manifest in the kinds of conduct Mr Tang engaged in (or, at least, stalking V in intrusive ways).

> (b)     In the case of Mr Tang’s AUD (or alcohol dependence), Mr Tang would have had to give in to his craving for alcohol, and as a result be disinhibited (according to Dr Lim) from engaging in his offending conduct.

30     In this light, it is more appropriate to say that Mr Tang’s condition—like that of the appellant in _Chong Yee Ka_—did not directly cause his offending, but instead caused difficulties controlling his emotions and impulses which eventually led to the loss (or non-exercise) of self-control that manifested in the offending conduct.

31     The **second, and related**, point is that Mr Tang’s actions were, to use the language in _Kong Peng Yee_, maladaptive responses to a mindset that was founded on true (or at least not imaginary) facts, and driven by some logic and rationality (as opposed to incoherence).

32     In this regard, Dr Zakir noted that Mr Tang was alert, calm and coherent, and he did not elicit any abnormalities with perceptions, cognition or insight.[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13) Likewise, Dr Low noted that Mr Tang had no evidence of thought disorder or perceptual disturbances.[^14] Dr Lim also noted that Mr Tang was relevant, open, cooperative, coherent in thinking.[^15]

33     In the present case, Mr Tang was beset with feelings of loss and betrayal he saw his (ex-)long-time girlfriend with another man even though she had reportedly broken up on the pretext of needing to look after her mother. He had taken to drinking to “numb” his pain, and saw V’s return to him as the “cure” to the problem. Mr Tang’s conduct, even if ill-considered from an enlightened perspective, was to him a rational means of trying to get V to return to him. Put another way, if V had returned to him at the material time, his conduct of stalking V would cease.

34     As Tay JA reasoned in _Kong Peng Yee_ at \[65\], in such cases, the mental disorder dissipates once the underlying situation is removed, and therefore ameliorates the criminal conduct only to a limited extent because the offender’s mind is still rational, and depression, even if severe, cannot be a license to harm others.[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16)

35      **Third**, I find that, for a number of the instances of stalking, Mr Tang had adequate mental faculties to know what he was doing[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17) (_ie_, to appreciate of the nature and quality of his conduct), and to exercise self-control.

> (a)      _First_, in the history recorded by Dr Zakir, Mr Tang recounted that he had imbibed on alcohol daily and stopped taking his heart medication to peruse V to reconcile and also to gain her attention, and he decided to stalk her when his initial acts failed. In other words, in the early stages, there is at least some thought given to what he was doing.

> (b)      _Next_, I am not prepared to accept Mr Tang’s claim that most acts of stalking were done when he was in a drunken stupor and that he could not remember them.[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18) Some of the e-mails were long (and not one-liners); and some demonstrated an awareness of prior events which also formed part of his course of conduct (such as stating places where Mr Tang visited in the hope of seeing V). Mr Tang would not have been tailing V’s vehicle on 1 October 2019 under the influence of alcohol (at least not to the extent that Mr Tang is unaware of what he is doing).

> (c)      _Third_, in relation to Mr Tang’s conduct when he was at V’s condominium on 1 October 2019, he had the presence of mind to tell the security officer that he was not a loanshark; I can think of no other reason why this was said other than for Mr Tang to justify his presence and his conduct, with a view to the security guard letting him continue knocking (or kicking) V’s door.

> (d)      _Finally_, in relation to Mr Tang’s Facebook post on 30 August 2019, Mr Tang reported to Dr Lim that he had posted a nasty post, took a screenshot, and then immediately deleted the post, as he had no intentions of harming or defaming her. The point is, to have deleted it immediately, he must have known of the harm it would have caused should the post remain on the SRC Facebook page (and, therefore, the wrongful quality or potential for harm of his conduct). To my mind, this shows the conduct of a person who had at least a minimal amount of planning, to cause some degree of alarm to V. Similarly, as the Prosecution points out, the fact that Mr Tang apologised shortly after sending the offending messages on the WhatsApp chat groups shows that he appreciated the quality of his conduct.[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19)

36     The corollary is that regular punishment is capable of instilling fear in Mr Tang and deterring him from such offending conduct in future,[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20) such that the principles of specific deterrence (or, for that matter, retribution) are not wholly displaced by the need for rehabilitation.

37      **Finally**, I note that Mr Tang’s Moderate DD is in full remission, whereas his AUD is in partial remission. In this sense, an MTO would only have the limited purpose of helping Mr Tang recover from his AUD (and, at best, preventing a relapse of either depression or AUD). In my judgment, the management of AUD is not something that requires rehabilitation outside of the prison context.

38     In fact, I am somewhat doubtful of the extent to which the AUD in this case should lead to an MTO. Self-induced intoxication is ordinarily an aggravating factor (_Wong Hoi Len v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2009\] 1 SLR(R) 115</span> (HC) _per_ V K Rajah JA). In that light, it would seem perverse, or at least concerning, if an offender could resort to alcohol as self-medication in response to a difficult situation, to the extent of becoming dependent on it (_ie_, in the sense of being afflicted with AUD), and, after engaging in offending conduct as a result of the disinhibition following the consumption of alcohol, succeed in arguing that the rehabilitative principle should take precedence (or mitigating value should be awarded) in respect of that offending behaviour. This would be tantamount to affording would-be offenders with a license (or even an incentive) to resort to alcohol and engage in offending conduct.[^21] I think these concerns apply especially given that Mr Tang’s AUD was not a pre-existing condition, but developed as a result of his response to his break-up with V.

39     Accordingly, I declined to make an MTO. I turn to consider what an appropriate sentence would be in this case.

### The appropriate fine/imprisonment

#### The applicable framework

40     A three-member High Court in _Lee Shing Chan v Public Prosecutor and another appeal_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] 4 SLR 1174</span> (“_Lee Shing Chan_”) at \[35\]–\[37\] set out the five-step sentencing framework for offences under s 7 PHA as follows:

> (a)     First, identify the harm caused by the offence, and the level of culpability, having regard to the offence-specific factors:

<table align="left" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="Judg-2-tblr" frame="all" pgwide="1"><colgroup><col width="49.32%"><col width="50.68%"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td align="left" class="br"
