41     Step 5 does not apply here since Mr Tang faces a single charge.

#### Step 1: Harm and culpability

42     Briefly, I find that both harm and culpability were at the borderline between low and moderate levels.

##### (1)   Culpability

43     In my view, Mr Tang’s culpability was borderline low/medium.

44     I disagreed with the Prosecution’s and Mr Tang’s submissions that Mr Tang’s culpability was, respectively, high[\[note: 22\]](#Ftn_22) and low.[^23]

(i)   Factors relevant to culpability

45      **First**, I address the volume (including the duration, frequency and regularity) of Mr Tang’s acts.

46     The **_duration_** of Mr Tang’s conduct is considerably long (at nearly 8 months), but the _volume_ of Mr Tang’s acts of stalking was not remarkably high or low. Seen in perspective, these numbers suggest that Mr Tang’s culpability is between low and moderate.

47     In terms of **_volume_**, I counted 64 incidents of stalking because each e-mail—there were 54—was counted as one incident. The remainder comprised 1 call to V’s friend, 2 messages to a WhatsApp group, 1 social media post, and 5 incidents in the physical realm. Several e-mails were sent within minutes of each other: if I considered an incident occurring within an hour of the last incident to form part of the same course of conduct, then the total incident count would only be about 50.

48     In terms of **_frequency/regularity_**, Mr Tang’s stalking was far from being a daily or even consistent affair.[\[note: 24\]](#Ftn_24) His conduct unfolded over 33 distinct calendar days. I note that there was no offending activity between 5 March 2019 and 19 May 2019 (_ie_, some 2.5 months). Between 25 July 2019 and 22 August 2019, he sent only 1 e-mail. There was also no activity between 5 September 2019 and 1 October 2019, and no activity between 2 October 2019 and 25 October 2019. In other words, there were significant periods amounting to 5–6 months where Mr Tang hardly stalked V.

49     Thus, it might be said that Mr Tang’s conduct unfolded over a prolonged duration and would have had the effect of reminding V of his presence (or his attempts to be present) in her life,[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25) but equally there were significant periods of respite in between.

50      **Second**, I address the nature of Mr Tang’s acts.

51     Essentially, the acts are not so sinister that Mr Tang’s culpability should be assessed to be high; neither are they so benign that his culpability should be considered low.

52     In terms of the **_modality/intrusiveness_** of Mr Tang’s conduct, 59—or most incidents—involved remote communications. Of these, 55 involved e-mails/text messages being sent to V, _ie_, a medium which is low on intrusiveness. 1 involved a call to V’s friend, 3 involved messages were broadcast to the public/third parties. What happened in the physical space were only 5 incidents (or, at most, 12 incidents, from the content of Mr Tang’s e-mails that he had been near V/V’s home, or tried to look for V at places she frequented),[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26) but this involved only 4 close-quarter interactions. Mr Tang’s conduct in the physical realm (whether in the SOF/charge, or inferred from his e-mails) was, apart from the incidents on 3 March 2019 and 1 October 2019, limited to a 2-month period (_ie_, 19 May–14 July 2019).

53     The Prosecution argued that the stalking is not less serious simply because it was done in the digital realm.[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27) I can accept that stalking is _not necessarily_ less serious when done in the digital realm. But, as I reasoned in _Public Prosecutor v Ng Wei Long_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] SGMC 78</span> (“_Ng Wei Long_”) at \[53\]–\[56\], the true principle appears to be whether the modality of stalking was exploited for the harms with which it is associated. Indeed, for the 3 messages/posts to third parties/the public, Mr Tang exploited the digital realm—or, to be more precise, gave V the impression that the digital realm wasexploited—for its potential to reach large groups of audiences quickly. But, this is not the case for Mr Tang’s e-mails. Intrusiveness—an indicium of the seriousness of the conduct—is measured by the amount of adjustment required by a victim to avoid the offender or the level of impedance to the victim’s right to free movement (_Lim Teck Kim v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] 5 SLR 279</span> (HC) (“_Lim Teck Kim_”) at \[30(b)\] _per_ Chan Seng Onn J). In this case, it would have required relatively little on V’s part to ignore Mr Tang’s e-mails.

54     Nonetheless, in terms of the **_tenor_** of Mr Tang’s conduct, I note that his acts were not all benign.

> (a)     In terms of his messages/e-mails to V, about one-third were innocuous or expressed longing/remorse towards V. These would probably have caused V little more than harassment/annoyance. However, about 40% of Mr Tang’s e-mails/messages to V were threatening/abusive/insulting/taunting, and the remainder (about 25%) sought to blame or guilt-trip V. Some of these messages were offensive to V’s religious beliefs.

> (b)     Of Mr Tang’s conduct in the physical realm, I found Mr Tang’s conduct more intrusive and rather less innocuous on 3 occasions: blocking V’s vehicle, trailing V’s vehicle, and kicking V’s door/using threatening language on the security officer.

55     In terms of the **_tendency of third-party communications to harm V_**, I do not think this was high. The call to V’s friend was essentially uneventful and harmless. The Facebook post and messages to the WhatsApp groups contained insults to V’s professional circle about V’s alleged promiscuity (“ready for a fuck but she will cheat your money. … She shallow sperm.”) or untrustworthiness (“Don’t trust this bitch.”);[\[note: 28\]](#Ftn_28) and to V’s social circle/to the public, about V’s alleged (lack of) religiosity, (“Act holy, go church, act hypocrite, she’s a bastard. She can ruin your family.”).[^29] However, no sensitive information was otherwise posted.

56      **Third**, and relatedly, I note that Mr Tang’s ultimate motive was to try to salvage his failed relationship. In this sense, I do not think that it is fair to characterise his conduct as being purely sinister.

57      **Fourth**, I address the issue of _mens rea_.

58     The Prosecution submits that:

> (a)     Mr Tang clearly intended to cause harassment and knew that his conduct was likely to cause harassment;[\[note: 30\]](#Ftn_30) and

> (b)     Mr Tang acted with a high degree of intentionality[\[note: 31\]](#Ftn_31) and awareness of his actions.[^32] On 1 October 2019, when V’s condominium security officers saw Mr Tang kicking V’s door, Mr Tang had the presence of mind to say that V owed him money and did not want to pay him back. Also, when he tailed V, he stopped only because V drove to a police station and police officers intervened.[^33]

59     As regards the intentionality of Mr Tang’s actions, I note at the outset that intending to cause harassment is not the same intending the acts/omissions forming the offending course of conduct. The latter does not necessarily entail an intention to cause harassment/alarm/distress, or even knowledge that harassment/alarm/distress is likely to be caused. Importantly, it cannot be overstated because, to make out an offence of stalking in the first place, a stalker would usually have to intend the acts/omissions that formed the offending course of conduct. It would seem strange to say that a person has stalked another by engaging in the kinds of acts/omissions in s 7(3) PHA with a lesser state of mind.

60     Ultimately, the _mens rea_ in the charge and SOF was that Mr Tang ought reasonably to have known that his conduct was likely to cause harassment/alarm to V. This is the lowest of three possible degrees of _mens rea_ (the other two being an intent to cause harassment/alarm/distress, and knowledge that one’s conduct is likely to cause harassment/alarm/distress).

61     While I agree that Mr Tang gave condominium security an excuse to try to continue his conduct, the overall effect of this on his culpability cannot be overstated since this does not indicate a meaningful degree of planning/premeditation, and ultimately concerned only one incident.

62      **Fifth**, the Prosecution submitted that Mr Tang’s culpability was enhanced because he sent V 2 further e-mails on 25 October 2019, after he was first charged in court and warned not to contact V.[\[note: 34\]](#Ftn_34)

63     However, Mr Tang only sent 2 e-mails within 12 minutes of each other, neither of which could be fairly characterised as threatening/abusive, or intended to blame/guilt-trip V. Instead, he said that he would not look for V again, and pleaded for V to forgive him (in the first e-mail) and to “settle this amicably” (in the second e-mail). In this light, I do not think too much can be made of it.

64      **Finally**, for completeness, I find that Mr Tang’s and V’s respective ages or age difference to be unremarkable.

65     It might seem that I have been lenient in assessing Mr Tang’s conduct. However, the gravity of the these factors—especially the first two—cannot be overstated, considering the views expressed in other decisions.

(ii)   Comparison with assessments of culpability in other decisions

66     I **first** consider _Lee Shing Chan_. This appeal involved two of three unlicensed fruit hawkers who, having been issued a summons for unlicensed hawking by National Environment Agency (“NEA”) officers, stalked those officers by driving their lorry and tailing the van used by the officers for 3 hours. The later part of this journey was characterised as “tailgating” as the lorry followed very closely, and the tailing ceased only when police officers intercepted the lorry. The Court held that the appellants’ culpability was “low … or perhaps the low end of medium” (at \[42\]), considering (1) the unsophisticated manner of tailing the victims’ van, (2) the _mens rea_ and apparent motive (in that case, it was an intention to cause alarm to the NEA officers), (3) the appellants’ knowledge that the victims were public officers going about their duties that evening, and (4) the fact that they were undeterred by the presence of an auxiliary police officer (“APO”).

67     In this case, Mr Tang had a lesser _mens rea_, and the issues of knowingly stalking a public officer on duty or being undeterred by an APO while stalking V also does not arise. Also, while the period for which Mr Tang tailed V is not stated in the papers, it does not appear to have approached 3 hours by any estimation. Even considering the duration and volume of his other conduct, I do not think that his culpability should be considerably higher than that of the appellants in _Lee Shing Chan_.

68     I **next** consider _Lim Teck Guan v Public Prosecutor_ (Magistrate’s Appeal No. 9889/2020/01) (“_Lim Teck Guan_”), which I find to be a useful and reliable reference because, apart from its factual matrix being sufficiently similar to the present case, it is an appellate decision affirming the only (published) first instance judgment reasoned with the benefit of the _Lee Shing Chan_ framework (see _Public Prosecutor v Lim Teck Guan_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGMC 2</span> (“_Lim Teck Guan_ (MC)”)).

69     There, the appellant, Lim, stalked the victim, his ex-girlfriend, for about 7 months following their break-up in March 2018. Lim had engaged in 5 (sets of) acts associated with stalking, namely:

> (a)     impersonating the victim on WeChat[\[note: 35\]](#Ftn_35) by creating a searchable account and posting compromising pictures of her (a cropped picture of himself and the victim topless in bed, although not showing her breasts), with sexually insulting captions, and threatening to add the victim’s friends to the account so they could access the photographs;

> (b)     sending multiple abusive and threatening messages over WeChat, Instagram[\[note: 36\]](#Ftn_36) and e-mail, such as “u going to die … I’ll make sure u disappear … U will regret”, and “otherwise I’ll harass the consultants in the list…I’ll make sure u get sacked by MOHH…That’s the sweetest revenge…u will see blood”;

> (c)     e-mailing the victim saying that he had waited for her many hours at the airport and also many times during lunchtime at her workplace, expressing his regrets and sincerity to resolve any misunderstandings between them;

> (d)     setting up 3 Instagram accounts to impersonate the victim and posting those same compromising photographs in 2 of them, which were publicly viewable for some periods of time within a span of about 6 days; and

> (e)     sending the victim some messages through a new WeChat account.

70     In this case, the Court agreed with the Prosecution and Lim that Lim’s culpability was “medium”, considering (1) his higher _mens rea_ of intending to cause the victim distress; (2) his breach of the victim’s trust in allowing compromising photographs to be taken during their relationship; (3) his planning and premeditation in impersonating the victim on WeChat and Instagram, compose the offending posts, and engage his audience, and waiting for the victim for many hours; (4) his self-interested motives in offending (_ie_, being blinded by a desire for closure and being unable to accept the abrupt end of his relationship)); and (5) the disruption he caused to the victim’s professional and personal life over a significant period of time (_Lim Teck Guan_ (MC) at \[28\]–\[34\]). The court also noted, as an aggravating factor, the fact that Lim, when told by the victim that she had made a police report, continued garnering followers for his (third) Instagram account for a few hours (at \[38\]).

71     The disruption Mr Tang caused to V’s life is more properly characterised as an indicium of harm (and not of culpability), and I will address it below.

72     As regards the other indicia of culpability, I note that Mr Tang’s course of conduct comprised more acts, and lasted slightly longer than the 6.5 months in _Lim Teck Guan_. However, Lim’s conduct was noticeably more severe. _First_, Lim impersonated his victim. _Second_, Lim had abused his victim’s trust (in taking compromising photographs) and had disseminated considerably more compromising material. _Third_, on the whole, I considered that Lim’s conduct revealed more premeditation/planning. _Fourth_, Lim had a higher _mens rea_. Accordingly, I think that Lim’s culpability should be slightly higher than Mr Tang’s.

##### (2)   Harm

73     In my view, the harm was at the top end of “slight”, or borderline slight/moderate.

74     I was not fully persuaded by either the Prosecution’s or Mr Tang’s submissions that the harm occasioned was, respectively, moderate[\[note: 37\]](#Ftn_37) or slight.[^38]

(i)   Modalities and degree of harm

75     As a preliminary point, I note that no Victim Impact Statement (“VIS”) was tendered in this case. The harms discussed here, therefore, are what appears in (or can be reasonably inferred from) the SOF.

76     I **first** address the harm to **V’s physical safety and freedom of movement**.

77     Overall, I consider that this kind of harm was relatively slight.

78     I note the following:

> (a)     Mr Tang did cause a real sense of threat to V’s safety by tailing V’s vehicle and kicking V’s condominium door on 1 October 2019. It was only after V drove to a police station and police officers intervened that Mr Tang ceased his conduct. Even so, Mr Tang scolded V at the police station, “Bastard. Act only.” Mr Tang’s conduct of kicking and knocking V’s condominium door later that evening was in my judgment clearly threatening. This was reinforced by the fact that, when condominium security arrived, he used threatening language and kicked the door aggressively. That said, I find the Prosecution’s position that this was done after Mr Tang had been produced in court[\[note: 39\]](#Ftn_39) to be incorrect, as he was charged in court 3 days later.

> (b)     Mr Tang did affect V’s safety (or, at least, affect V’s freedom of movement) when he blocked her car on 19 May 2019. In this regard, I note that V threatened to call security before Mr Tang moved his vehicle to allow V to drive off.[\[note: 40\]](#Ftn_40)

> (c)     Mr Tang affected V’s sense of freedom of movement by:

>> (i)       threatening to appear at a line dancing event that V intended to attend on 31 August 2019 and to “make \[her\] famous”, causing V to cancel her plans to attend the event;[\[note: 41\]](#Ftn_41) and

>> (ii)       telling V that he had been looking for her at places she used to frequent, causing V to feel distressed and paranoid about going to those places.[\[note: 42\]](#Ftn_42)

79     Mr Tang submitted that V knew that he would not cause her any harm,[\[note: 43\]](#Ftn_43) and that his conduct merely caused “annoyance” and “inconvenience” to V.[^44] On the other hand, the Prosecution also submitted that Mr Tang also threatened V’s physical safety by threatening to appear at the line dancing event, and by physically appearing at V’s condominium on several occasions.[^45]

80     However, I am not fully persuaded by these submissions.

81     The fact that Mr Tang physically appeared near V may represent a level of intrusion into V’s life, but it does not necessarily entail a threat to V’s physical safety.

82     Specifically, these other incidents cited by the Prosecution do not disclose threats to V’s personal safety. Mr Tang’s threat to appear at the line dancing event appears to have been a threat to V’s reputation, considering the sexually insulting messages that Mr Tang had posted on the SRC Facebook page. Indeed, the Prosecution concedes that V had told the Investigating Officer, when recording her first statement, that Mr Tang would not harm her.[\[note: 46\]](#Ftn_46) In other words, V broadly perceived Mr Tang’s threats to be hollow. However, I note that:

> (a)     V reported worrying for her safety after the scene Mr Tang created outside her home and at the police station (_ie_, on 1 October 2019).[\[note: 47\]](#Ftn_47) While this claim was not raised the SOF earlier, I accept it as being very likely. The 1 October 2019 incidents posed a materially larger threat to V’s physical safety than any of the preceding incidents, and the fact that V drove to the police station is a reliable indication of how threatened she felt.

> (b)     Mr Tang, in using his car to block V’s car on 19 May 2019, had put both cars at risk of an accident. Calling this incident an “inconvenience” is to trivialise the harm done to V on this occasion.

83      **Next**, I address the harm to **V’s reputation**.

84     Overall, I consider the harm here to be limited.

85     V’s reputation was affected by Mr Tang publishing degrading comments about V’s alleged promiscuity/untrustworthiness to V’s professional circle; and about V’s alleged (lack of) religiosity to V’s social circle/the public.

86     In this regard, Mr Tang submits that the “UAG 2019” and “PN Broadcast” WhatsApp chat groups are the same, and that the name of the chat group had merely been changed.[\[note: 48\]](#Ftn_48) Presumably, this was intended to show that Mr Tang’s messages reached fewer people than it appeared to have reached. However, I do not think this is likely. There was no further explanation for Mr Tang’s claim, and it sits uncomfortably with the fact that, at the respective material times, the UAG 2019 group had about 118 members, while the PN Broadcast group had only about 61 members. More importantly, it seems to contradict the SOF, which mentions 2 work-related chat groups.

87     Nonetheless, I do not think these messages had a large reach. Mr Tang claims that he had deleted them within a few seconds of sending/making them and that no one spoke to him about those posts, with the consequence that I should infer that none of V’s colleagues/friends knew about those messages/posts. On the other hand, the Prosecution claimed that V’s friends had seen these messages and informed V about it.[\[note: 49\]](#Ftn_49) It is not clear how many people saw Mr Tang’s messages, or whether Mr Tang’s messages were deleted as quickly as he had claimed. But, it is undisputed that the SRC Facebook page is a publicly accessible page[^50] “liked” by 2,749 people (I regard this as a proxy of the number of persons interested in what happens on the SRC Facebook page). The “UAG 2019” and “PN Broadcast” groups had, at the material time, 118 and 61 members respectively. The number of potential viewers of the SRC Facebook page is large. While the WhatsApp groups were smaller in comparison, it seems that the eventual reach of the Facebook post and WhatsApp messages would have been comparable because WhatsApp is almost invariably linked to one’s mobile device (and therefore represents a more direct and instantaneous form of communication than Facebook). Ultimately, the fair inference in my judgment is that even if the messages were deleted soon after, at least a small number of people would have had a fleeting glance at the message.

88     I also note that Mr Tang’s messages, although degrading, were also crude and unsophisticated. In my view, the crudeness of these messages would detract somewhat from their intended effect on readers, in the sense that readers would be less likely to believe or place weight on what Mr Tang wrote. I also note that Mr Tang apologised and essentially retracted what he said—I address this in more detail below, but it suffices to say that the members of the UAG Group would be less likely, upon seeing the apology, to believe the claims in Mr Tang’s earlier messages to be true.

89      **Third**, I note that Mr Tang’s conduct had negligible impact on third parties.[\[note: 51\]](#Ftn_51) He had called one of V’s friends in an attempt to look for V, but this was a one-off incident.[^52]

90     Again, if it seems that I have been lenient in assessing the harm occasioned, the gravity of the these harms should not be overstated, considering the views expressed in other decisions.

(ii)   Comparison with assessments of harm in other decisions

91     I **first** compare this case to _Lee Shing Chan_ (the facts of which are recited at \[66\] above).

92     It will be recalled that the NEA officers were followed (and, at the latter part of the journey, “tailgat\[ed\]”) for 3 hours. At trial, they testified that they were alarmed and worried for their safety, including being concerned about being followed to their homes. Even so, the court considered that “minimal harm” was caused to the victims, and harm would be assessed as “slight” for the purpose of the sentencing bands (at \[40\] and \[42\]).

93     The overall incursion on V’s physical safety/freedom of movement in this case is comparable. Apart from tailing V, Mr Tang had kicked V’s condominium door, blocked V’s car, and affected V’s sense of freedom of movement. However, this is compensated for by the fact that V was not tailed a long period, or in such a dangerous manner. Considering the additional harm to V’s reputation—which I find to be limited—the overall harm in this case should not be much higher than the “minimal” harm assessed in _Lee Shing Chan_.

94     I **next** compare this case to _Lim Teck Guan_. A VIS was tendered in that case. The court agreed with the Prosecution that the harm caused was moderate (_Lim Teck Guan_ (MC) at \[23\]–\[27\]), considering that:

> (a)     Lim had damaged the victim’s reputation, as colleagues, friends and strangers had seen compromising photographs of her (even if not amounting to explicit nudity) with captions containing sexual innuendoes, and had approached her about the incident. Lim had also identified the victim’s occupation and place of work. Notably, Lim had sent follower requests to other social media accounts.

> (b)     Lim had caused V distress by issuing threats on the victim’s life, threats to cause her to be dismissed from her job, and threats to harass her colleagues.

> (c)     Lim had affected third parties by posting a contact list of the victim’s associates/colleagues on the publicly-accessible account used to impersonate the victim. He had also asked the victim’s ex-boyfriend to consider telling the victim’s mother about what he perceived to be a negative influence on her by her long-time classmate.

95     The court also noted the disruption he caused to the victim’s professional and personal life over a significant period of time (_Lim Teck Guan_ (MC) at \[32\]).

96     The disruption Mr Tang caused to V’s life unfolded over a slightly longer duration and through more incidents, but, in my judgment, the harm caused by Mr Tang is noticeably lower. Each incident in this case was less severe. I note the following points:

> (a)     Mr Tang’s conduct (unlike Lim’s) had a negligible impact on third parties.

> (b)     While Mr Tang had used threatening words on V, those threats were less specific and (if anything) suggestive of ruining V’s reputation. I do think that this, on the whole, are not as severe as those that Lim issued on his victim’s life, employment, and colleagues.

> (c)     Mr Tang caused a considerably lower impact to V’s reputation than Lim did to his victim. _First_, there was no compromising photographs of V posted. In contrast, Lim posted some compromising photographs of V, and photographs of the back of an unknown female in undergarments (apparently intended to give the impression that it was V). _Next_, I consider the reach of Mr Tang’s messages to have been rather more limited. The compromising photographs posted by Lim were, at various times, made publicly available on 2 social media platforms. On Instagram, the photographs were posted on two of the three accounts created by Lim. The first account had 45 “followers” and had “followed” 600 others at the material time; and the three accounts in aggregate survived for about 6 calendar days. The VIS filed in _Lim Teck Guan_ revealed that the compromising photographs had been circulated at the victim’s workplace. Among other things, the victim also claimed in her VIS to have lost her appetite and interest in daily activities, to have sleeping difficulties, to have taken down her social media accounts, and to have changed her address and mobile number. These facts are broadly not present here.

97     In this light, I do not think that the harm caused by Mr Tang can be fairly said to rise to the “moderate” level assessed in _Lim Teck Guan_. Instead, I think that the harm in this case should fairly be assessed to be at the top end of “slight” harm, or at the border of slight/moderate harm.

#### Steps 2 and 3: Indicative sentencing range, appropriate starting point

98     In my view, the appropriate sentencing band is the top end of slight harm and at the borderline of low/medium culpability, and the starting point would be 3 months’ imprisonment. For clarity, I have indicated the indicative starting point below.

![](data:image;base64,)

99     I note that if the matrix is read such that a 2-month imprisonment term is given for the most serious of the “slight harm/low culpability” band, but a 4-month imprisonment term is given for the least serious of the “moderate harm/medium culpability” band, this would result in a situation where diagonally adjacent bands are discontinuous. In other words, under this reading, an infinitesimal increase in both harm and culpability could lead to a 2-month imprisonment term becoming a 4-month imprisonment term (or a 6-month imprisonment term becoming a 9-month imprisonment term).

![](data:image;base64,)

100    As this leads to a strange result, I do not think the matrix was intended to be applied this way. It seems to me that the ranges posited in _Lee Shing Chan_ are principally for cases which fall neatly into a single cell in the matrix, and not for cases at the borderline between cells. In my view, the appropriate starting point, where harm is on the borderline between slight and moderate and where culpability is on the borderline between low and medium, is one which is higher than the 2 months’ imprisonment (for the top ends of “low culpability” and “slight harm”), but lower than the 4+ months’ imprisonment (for the bottom ends of “medium culpability” and “moderate harm”). A 3-month term, being the midpoint of these 2 points, is a fair starting point. On this footing, I think that the custodial threshold has been crossed by a clear margin, and that the maximum fine would be wholly insufficient to capture the gravity of the offence.

101    In my view, this starting point is fair, in comparison to the starting points of 2 weeks identified in _Lee Shing Chan_ at \[42\] for “slight” (or “minimal”) harm and “low … or perhaps the low end of medium” culpability, and of 5 months identified in _Lim Teck Guan_ (MC) at \[37\] for “moderate” harm and “medium” culpability:

![](data:image;base64,)

#### Step 4: Personal aggravating or mitigating factors

102    At this juncture, I note that the Prosecution did not submit that Mr Tang had relevant antecedents that amounted to an aggravating factor.

103    I will discuss 3 factors which Mr Tang submitted to be mitigating.

104     **First**, I note that Mr Tang elected without undue delay to plead guilty.

105     **Second**, I also find Mr Tang’s apologies partially mitigating. In this regard, there are 2 apologies.

106    The _first_ apology pertains to the messages on the “UAG 2019” WhatsApp group. On 5 March 2019, Mr Tang sent an apology in the chat group:

> With respect to all the comments that I have posted in the company chat group in relation to Ms \[V\], I, Jeffrey Tang Yan Jiang hereby unreservedly and irrevocably apologise to Ms \[V\] for the fact that those comments are totally untrue, baseless and uncalled for.

> Sorry pals for the inconvenienced caused. Shouldn’t have let personal issues carried into work group.

107    The Prosecution, highlighting the phrase “Sorry pals for the inconvenience caused”, argues that the apology is “hardly a sincere” one.[\[note: 53\]](#Ftn_53) The choice of the word “inconvenience” may not have fully expressed what Mr Tang ought to be sorry for, but, in my view, this argument places undue focus on the casual-sounding part of the apology, since the use of the word “pals” is explicable on the basis that the audience comprised Mr Tang’s colleagues. More importantly, it ignores the more serious portions that flank this sentence on both sides (_ie_, “unreservedly and irrevocably apologise … for … totally untrue, baseless and uncalled for \[comments\]” and “Shouldn’t have let personal issues carried into work group”). In my judgment, there is some sincerity in this apology.

108    The _second_ set of apologies pertains to the apology which Mr Tang addressed to V and annexed to his mitigation plea.[\[note: 54\]](#Ftn_54) However, I am less impressed by this apology. _First_, this apology came well after Mr Tang was charged in court. In fact, Mr Tang sent V 2 e-mails he sent after having been produced in court and warned not to contact V, but in neither of them did he directly apologise for his conduct (I note, however, that he asked for V’s forgiveness in the first of these e-mails). _Second_, while it contained an apparently heartfelt admission of wrongdoing and a desire for forgiveness, it also—like what Mr Tang alluded to in those 2 e-mails—appealed to V’s pity (both on him and on his aged mother) to drop the criminal charges against him. For these reasons, I do not consider this apology to have been as sincere.

109     **Third**, Mr Tang further submits that there was substantial diminution in his ability to exercise self-control, and impairment of his consciousness, in the light of his Moderate DD and AUD at the time of the offence. He also claims that, in many cases, he had acted in a drunken stupor and could not remember his conduct, and realised what he had done only when he had sobered up.

110    In my view, these contentions have limited mitigating value.

111     _First_, as I have discussed above, I am not satisfied that Mr Tang’s low mood or alcohol had substantially impaired Mr Tang’s control over, or appreciation of the quality of, his conduct. The most that I think can be said is that his judgment was clouded to a small extent by his Moderate DD, and to a larger extent by his AUD, and this made him more predisposed to his offending conduct.

112     _Second_, if Mr Tang truly did not mean the threats or insults he had written in his e-mails, he could have clarified at the first available opportunity that he had written them in a drunken stupor, and ask that they be ignored. This was not done: some threatening messages were simply sent without any follow-up soon after, while others were followed up by messages suggesting that Mr Tang wanted to inflict self-harm or end his life (and thus either blaming or guilt-tripping V).

113    In the final analysis, the mitigating value in this case flows largely from the guilty plea and Mr Tang’s first apology, and (to a limited extent) the Moderate DD which made Mr Tang slightly more predisposed to his offending conduct.

#### Final sentence

114    In my judgment, the indicative sentence of 3 months’ imprisonment should be discounted to 9 weeks’ imprisonment on account of the mitigating factors. In my view, this is a punishment that would fairly fit both the crime and offender.

### Comparison with other precedents

115    A number of other precedents were cited for my consideration. Both parties cited _Tan Yao Min v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 3 SLR 1134</span> (HC) (“_Tan Yao Min_”) and _Public Prosecutor v Tan Boon Wah_ (SC-905671-2016) (“_Tan Boon Wah_”), and in addition Mr Tang cited _Public Prosecutor v Lai Zhi Heng_ (SC-912644-2015) (“_Lai Zhi Heng_”) and _Public Prosecutor v Adrian Goh Guan Kiong_ (SC-902574-2016) (“_Adrian Goh_”).

116    The Prosecution, relying on _Public Prosecutor v Ng Han Wei_ (SC-912985-2016) and _Public Prosecutor v Moh Yan Chung_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] SGDC 46</span> for the proposition that imprisonment terms of 5–6 months have been imposed where the stalking took place purely in the physical realm or in the digital realm,[^55] argues that a 6–8 month imprisonment term is warranted where stalking took place in both the physical and digital realms, and continued after court proceedings commenced.[^56]

117    Respectfully, I cannot accept Prosecution’s argument. I have explained at \[63\] above why the fact that Mr Tang’s conduct continued after court proceedings commenced cannot be overstated. In my view, it simply does not follow that stalking over multiple realms is necessarily worse than stalking over a purely physical realm, or that this attracts imprisonment terms of 5–6 months. The inquiry is not so much the mode of stalking, but whether that mode was exploited for the harms with which it is associated. Further, this argument ignores the other factors necessary to arrive at a just sentence. It also ignores the fact that lower sentences have been given in other cases (_eg_, 3 months imprisonment was given in _Public Prosecutor v Tan Khoon Aik, Nelson_ (SC-913209-2016), even though the stalking took place over 1.5 years, or more than twice the duration of the present case, in both the physical and digital realms).

118    Another point—and this applies both the Prosecution’s submission on the modality of stalking, and to the parties’ reliance on precedents that predated _Lee Shing Chan_—is that some these decisions have been criticised on the basis that the sentences have congregated around a point (and failed to utilise the full sentencing range) (_Lim Teck Kim_ at \[55\] _et seq_) or appear inconsistent with each other (_Ng Wei Long_ at \[46\]). In my view, it is unclear whether these decisions would be regarded as correctly decided under the _Lee Shing Chan_ framework. While _Lee Shing Chan_ did not specifically pass any adverse comments on these decisions, the court’s sentiment at \[34\] (_ie_, that analogising from precedents is unsatisfactory because the lack of structure and guidance does not conduce to consistency across cases) is not inconsistent with the concerns previously expressed over these precedents.

119    I will examine 4 decisions: _Ng Han Wei_, _Adrian Goh­_, _Tan Boon Wah_, and _Lai Zhi Heng_. Among the decisions cited for my consideration, these were in my view the most comparable (in terms of the sentence imposed). A 6-month imprisonment term was given in each of these cases, save for _Ng Han Wei_, where 5 months’ imprisonment was imposed. However, it was posited in _Lim Teck Kim_ that the sentences for these 4 cases should have been 1.6, 4.2, 4.8 and 11.6 months’ imprisonment, respectively, under Chan J’s points framework. I will explain why the gravity of the offence in this case is not necessarily worse than _Ng Han Wei_, and is materially lower than _Adrian Goh­_, _Tan Boon Wah_, and _Lai Zhi Heng_. It should follow that, _a fortiori_, the gravity of the offence in this case is even lower when compared to _Tan Yao Min_, where an 8-month imprisonment term was imposed.

#### Ng Han Wei

120    In _Ng Han Wei_, the offender, then aged 24, pleaded guilty to unlawfully stalking a girl, then aged 12, by:

> (a)     loitering at a staircase landing at the block of flats where she lived, following her into the lift, following her to her school, and asking her “why did you walk so fast?”;

> (b)     10 days later, loitering at the same staircase landing, entering the lift while she was inside (although on a different floor), asking for her name and if she had a mobile phone, following her until she had reached a different block of flats, and asking her for her favourite colour and whether he could kiss her; and

> (c)     1 day thereafter, walking past the flat where the victim stayed (while she was inside) and looking inside her unit (on this occasion, while he waited at the same staircase landing, he did not take the same lift as her as she was accompanied by her brother).

121    While the offender was sentenced to 5 months’ imprisonment, I have explained my concerns in _Ng Wei Long_ at \[46(b)\] that the sentence in _Ng Han Wei_ seems to fall on the firm side. In fact, Chan Seng Onn J in _Lim Teck Kim_ thought that the sentence ought to have been in the region of 2 months’ imprisonment (_ie_, Chan J thought that the sentence was excessive by a duration of 3 months’ imprisonment, or by a factor of 150%). Among all the decisions Chan J reviewed with reference to his points framework, this represents the largest excess in the actual sentence compared to the putative sentence (_ie_, Chan J would have found this sentence most manifestly excessive).

122    With this caveat in mind, I now explain why I do not think the gravity of the offence here is necessarily worse than in _Ng Han Wei_.

123     **_First_**, in terms of culpability, I accept that the duration and frequency of stalking here is considerably more severe. However, I consider that this is outweighed by the other factors. For example, the victim in _Ng Han Wei_ is far more vulnerable by virtue of the victim’s age and the age difference between victim and offender. The conduct was premeditated to a higher degree, as the offender had followed the victim to her home. The _mens rea_ in _Ng Han Wei_ also involved an intent to harass, and the offender harboured sinister motives.

124     **_Second_**, in terms of harm caused, I note that the sense of threat to the victim’s safety led to self-help measures being taken (in the form of being accompanied by her brother).

125     **_Third_**, the offender had 3 relatively recent and similar antecedents, which would be a highly aggravating factor:

> (a)     8 years prior, he was convicted of 2 counts of outrage of modesty of an under-14 girl (with 1 more count taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing (“TIC”)), and sentenced to probation and to reside at a juvenile home for 30 months.

> (b)     5 years prior, he was convicted of 3 counts of outrage of modesty (with 2 more counts TIC), and was sentenced to reformative training.

> (c)     1 year prior, he was convicted of 1 count of insulting a woman’s modesty under s 509 of the PC by taking an upskirt photograph (with 2 more counts TIC), and sentenced to 4 weeks’ imprisonment.

#### Adrian Goh

126    In _Adrian Goh_, the offender pleaded guilty to unlawfully stalking his girlfriend of some 3 years (but with whom his relationship was strained). He had felt insecure about the victim’s close relationship with several male colleagues and resentful and upset that she was travelling to Kuala Lumpur with a male colleague (“her Colleague”), and thus did the following:

> (a)     One day, when the victim entrusted her mobile phone to the offender over lunch, he used her mobile phone to send, to a WhatsApp chat group comprising colleagues and superiors (_ie_, such that the content appeared to originate from her), 4 nude photographs of her (which he had taken with her consent over the course of their relationship, on the condition that he did not disseminate them) and 2 messages suggesting that the victim was having an affair with her Colleague. He thereafter deleted those messages from her phone and reacted to queries from her colleagues in a way that sought to dispel suspicions that her phone had been hacked.

> (b)     3 days later, he used a fictitious account, pretended to represent a group of concerned colleagues, and sent an e-mail to the victim’s superior, baselessly and falsely alleging that the victim and her Colleague were having sex in their workplace uniform.

> (c)     On that day, he also posted a letter to the victim’s home and addressed to her father, pretending to represent the victim’s church, suggesting that church-goers had found out that she was going overseas to have pre-marital sex with multiple partners, knowing that her family, being staunch Christians, would disapprove of such conduct.

127    The offender was sentenced to 6 months’ imprisonment. Again, the gravity of the offence there was considerably higher.

128     **_First_**, the culpability in _Adrian Goh_ was higher on the whole (or, at worst, comparable), even though Mr Tang’s course of conduct was significantly longer and involved more incidents. The _mens rea_ in _Adrian Goh_ was that of intention to cause harassment. There was also an abuse of the trust reposed in him by the victim, and an attempt to conceal his conduct. The court remarked that the offender had embarked on “a deliberated and calculated plan” to disseminate the victim’s nude images, with an intent not only to embarrass and humiliate the victim, [\[note: 57\]](#Ftn_57) cause her family to disapprove of her supposed behaviour and harm her reputation,[^58] but also to stymie both her and her Colleague’s careers.[^59]

129     **_Second_**, the harm occasioned in _Adrian Goh_ was much higher. _First_, the victim experienced more harm: she suffered countless sleepless nights for some time, and took leave for 10 days after the incident as she did not know how to face her colleagues. She was also afraid to see the offender on the street as she feared he would beat her up, and was afraid to enter a new romantic relationship for some time. In this regard, the DJ held that the effects of the stalking were “long lasting”.[\[note: 60\]](#Ftn_60)_Second_, a third party was also adversely affected.

130     **_Third_**, in _Adrian Goh_, another charge was taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing (knowingly possessing 331 obscene films under s 30(2)(_a_) of the Films Act (Cap 107, 1998 Rev Ed)).

#### Tan Boon Wah

131    In _Tan Boon Wah_, the offender pleaded guilty to unlawfully stalking his former male partner (with whom he had been in a relationship for some 4 years) for slightly more than 1 year.[\[note: 61\]](#Ftn_61) The bulk of the stalking[^62] comprised the following:

> (a)     loitering outside the victim’s residence on a daily basis in the morning (_ie_, from around 6 am to 7.30am) and at night (from between 6 pm and 9 pm to approximately 11pm, when the victim had turned off the lights in his unit), and outside the victim’s army camp (where he was serving national service) on a daily basis in the evening, and attempting to confront and converse with him when he appeared.

> (b)     following the victim on numerous occasions (to places that he frequented).

> (c)     making numerous harassing phone calls and sending numerous harassing text messages and e-mails to the victim. As regards the calls, he would use both his mobile phone number, Skype Voice-over-IP to make calls that registered as private number calls, and spoofed numbers that were either unusual or belonged to the victim’s friends and families and official hotlines (including the National Service hotline, the SingTel hotline, Jurong Police Division, and Police and Fire emergency hotlines).[\[note: 63\]](#Ftn_63) The e-mails would contain questions about specific places the offender had seen the victim at (thus giving the impression that the victim was under surveillance), or expressing his determination not to desist from his behaviour.

> (d)     uploading on his Facebook account photographs of both of them kissing, and threatening to disseminate them to the victim’s acquaintances unless the victim e-mailed/called him.

> (e)     e-mailing the victim photographs of him in the nude taken without his consent, intending to compel the victim to reply to his e-mail.[\[note: 64\]](#Ftn_64)

132    The court sentenced the offender to 6 months’ imprisonment (the sentence sought by the Prosecution). However, again, I find Mr Tang’s overall criminality to be significantly lower.

133     **_First_**, in _Tan Boon Wah_, the offender’s culpability would have been significantly higher. The duration of stalking was longer, and its frequency far higher. The victim there faced daily harassment and even received up to 1,408 calls in a single day. On at least 4 other days, he received some 700–900 missed calls.[\[note: 65\]](#Ftn_65) When he placed his phone on do-not-disturb mode in response to the stalking, the offender sent him a taunting e-mail, suggesting that he might miss important e-mails from the government or army. The offender also circulated moderately compromising photographs to a closed group of third parties, and threatened to disseminate those photographs to a wider class of persons.

134     **_Second_**, the harm caused to that victim[\[note: 66\]](#Ftn_66) was also far worse:

> (a)     The victim’s father had to accompany the victim out of his home every morning to prevent him from being harassed by the offender (and to capture his actions as evidence),[\[note: 67\]](#Ftn_67) and the family had to install a CCTV outside their unit costing about $1,000.[^68]

> (b)     The victim had to take a taxi home from his camp every day (instead of the bus or train), and had to take roundabout routes to the places he frequented. He estimated that this would have added a “few thousand dollars” to his expenses.[\[note: 69\]](#Ftn_69)

> (c)     The victim had to change his phone number each time the offender managed to obtain his new number, and to buy a second phone to receive calls from people apart from family and friends. His expenses in this regard totalled $2,100.

> (d)     The victim was distressed that the offender’s daily presence outside his army camp came to his colleagues’ and superiors’ attention, and he developed a distrust of others. He also experienced many disputes with his family because of the stalking.[\[note: 70\]](#Ftn_70) This led to the victim seeking one session of counselling.[^71]

> (e)     That the victim had lodged 22 police reports over the course of the stalking is indicative of its effect on him.

135     **_Third_**, the offender in _Tan Boon Wah_ faced other charges. Apart from being convicted on 1 count of obtaining access to the victim’s personal data under s 51(1) of the Personal Data Protection Act 2012 (Act 26 of 2012), for which he was sentenced to 2 months’ (concurrent) imprisonment (this involved requesting for the victim’s new mobile phone number by holding himself out as the victim and furnishing the victim’s personal particulars acquired in the course of their prior relationship),[\[note: 72\]](#Ftn_72) a further count of cheating by personation under s 419 of the PC was taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing (this involved dishonestly inducing delivery of a parcel meant for the victim from the postman, by holding himself out as the victim).[^73]

#### Lai Zhi Heng

136    In _Lai Zhi Heng_, the offender pleaded guilty to unlawfully stalking the victim (a girl with whom he had been in a brief sexual relationship) for about 1 year. This included:

> (a)     following the victim on numerous occasions (and, on one occasion, following her in his car such that he had to brake hard at one point to avoid hitting her);[\[note: 74\]](#Ftn_74)

> (b)     sending numerous harassing WhatsApp and text messages to her;[\[note: 75\]](#Ftn_75)

> (c)     threatening to release the victim’s nude photographs unless she complied with his requests (including requests to meet him and send more nude photographs of herself); and

> (d)     disseminating, in the vicinity of the victim’s residence (including placing on the walls/in the lifts and in the letter boxes of the victim’s block of flats),[\[note: 76\]](#Ftn_76) flyers with the victim’s nude photographs (and accompanying harassing messages) and pamphlets containing the victim’s personal information and, on 3 occasions, uploading the victim’s nude photographs and messages alleging that she was a prostitute onto a Facebook group for the co-curricular activity in her new school (to which she had transferred in a bid to avoid the stalking).

137    The court sentenced the offender to 6 months’ imprisonment. However, I find Mr Tang’s overall criminality to be significantly lower.

138     **_First_**, the culpability in _Lai Zhi Heng_ was much higher. The victim was aged 18–19 the time of the offence while the offender was aged 25–26. The stalking unfolded over a longer duration. The offender obtained 30 nude photographs of the victim through threats, which photographs were then used to further subsequent threats. When the victim tried to get the offender to stop putting up the flyers, the accused extracted an “apology” by forcing her to write 200 lines.

139     **_Second_**, the harm in _Lai Zhi Heng_ was much higher. Apart from physically endangering the victim (their vehicles had a near-accident), the offender also harmed the victim’s reputation. The offender disseminated sensitive information and highly compromising photographs to various group of persons including the public. As a result, the victim became afraid to travel alone and her mother had to quit her job to escort her to and from school.[\[note: 77\]](#Ftn_77) The victim ended up changing schools twice to try to avoid the harassment.[^78] The public dissemination of nude photos caused the victim trauma, lost her friends,[^79] and made her contemplate suicide and seek psychiatric help.[^80]

140     **_Third_**, a further charge was taken into consideration for sentencing: it involved unlawfully stalking the victim for a further 3-month period shortly thereafter. This involved following the victim, preventing her from boarding a train in an attempt to speak with her, leaving harassing messages addressed to her at public locations near her home, and leaving unsolicited sums of money under the front door of her home.[\[note: 81\]](#Ftn_81)

## Conclusion

141    In conclusion, I ordered that Mr Tang be imprisoned for 9 weeks, and that the sentence commence in 15 days’ time.

142    Both parties have since filed cross-appeals against sentence. Mr Tang was granted bail pending the hearing of the appeals.
